<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCA6A75FD279AF1140BBA57" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCA6A75FD279AF1140BBA57" blockId="49.[730,1324,3047,3470]" lastBlockId="49.[1398,2609,284,1663]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">
Placement of 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75FC629AF11A80B7FB" authorityName="Kitchener, How &amp; Maharadatunkamsi" authorityYear="1991" box="[926,1152,3240,3273]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="heran">Nyctophilus heran</taxonomicName>
in a species group is uncertain. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75FD279AAE1D66B62A" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1821" box="[731,870,3319,3352]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="geoffroyi">N. geoffroyi</taxonomicName>
and is tentatively included in the 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75FD269B471D3FB60D" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1821" box="[730,831,3358,3391]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="geoffroyi">geoffroyi</taxonomicName>
species group. There were apparently recently obtained specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75FB0A9B1C1D3DB6BC" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1821" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Nyctophilus</taxonomicName>
on Timor that apparently resembled 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75FA3F97451835BA0F" authorityName="Kitchener, How &amp; Maharadatunkamsi" authorityYear="1991" box="[1475,1589,284,317]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="heran">N. heran</taxonomicName>
, but a comparison of these samples to other 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75F74C97451741BA0F" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1821" box="[2224,2369,284,317]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Nyctophilus</taxonomicName>
has not yet been undertaken, and the name 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75F904971D197ABA57" baseAuthorityName="E. Geoffroy" baseAuthorityYear="1806" box="[1784,1914,324,357]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="timoriensis">timoriensis</taxonomicName>
will continue to go unused for now. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCA6A75FA8797321794BABE" box="[1403,2452,363,396]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" type="distribution">
<caption id="90EB6676FFCA6A75FA8797321794BABE" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6397962" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6397962" box="[1403,2452,363,396]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6397962/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" targetBox="[114,706,3047,3461]" targetPageId="49">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCA6A75FA8797321794BABE" blockId="49.[1398,2609,284,1663]" box="[1403,2452,363,396]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFCA6A75FA879732182BBABE" bold="true" box="[1403,1579,363,396]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from type locality on Lembata I, Lesser Sunda Is.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCA6A75FA8797CE17B3BF93" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" type="description">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCA6A75FA8797CE17B3BF93" blockId="49.[1398,2609,284,1663]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFCA6A75FA8797CE186FBA86" bold="true" box="[1403,1647,407,436]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 51-5 mm, tail 40-7 mm, ear 23-4 mm, hindfoot 6-4 mm, forearm 39-3 mm; weight 7-6 g (type specimen). The Sunda Long-eared Bat has very large ears and unique simple noseleaf consisting of two ridges, one further on muzzle and another immediately above nostrils, with vertical groove in middle and furred trough between them. Dorsal pelage is light drab brown; venter is paler. Face, ears, and wing membranes are light buff. Rostrum is short and blunt, with ridge across muzzle over nostrils that is well developed and high, with paired mounds joined medially by a conspicuous membrane that expands distally to form a Y-shaped groove. Ears are very large and broad, with bluntly roundedtip, horizontal ribbing on inner surfaces, inward curved anterior edges, and smooth posterior edges (ears can fold back at top ofthick part of anterior edge); large and furred interauricular band crosses forehead between ears; tragus is moderately long and bluntly rounded at tip, being practically straight on anterior margin. Glans penisis slender and lacks very prominent distal lobe; urethral lobe is ventrally U-shaped;it differs from the Lesser Long-eared Bat (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCA6A75F7AD95CA16DFB886" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1821" box="[2129,2271,915,948]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="geoffroyi">N. geoffroyi</taxonomicName>
) in lacking pronounced dorsal crest and distal lobe that overshoots ventral mound. Baculum has moderately thin shaft in dorsal view, tapering to non-bifurcated tip, base being strongly bifurcated; in lateral view, baculum is curved downward at base, but shaftis straight to pointed tip. Skull is generally similar to the Lesser Long-eared Bat,sagittal crest is weak, rostrum is slightly more depressed and median sulcusis slightly deeper than in the Lesser Long-eared Bat, tympanic bullae are relatively inflated, and M” and M, are moderately reduced.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCA6A75FA8492F11925BE24" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCA6A75FA8492F11925BE24" blockId="49.[1398,2609,284,1663]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFCA6A75FA8492F11BE8BFFB" bold="true" box="[1400,1512,1192,1225]" pageId="49" pageNumber="807">Habitat.</emphasis>
Type specimen was collected over a small stagnant poolin a small dry stream 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFFCA6A75FA8592891BCEBFC3" box="[1401,1486,1232,1265]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="49" pageNumber="807" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
from mangrovesat sea level. Native gardens and occasionally banana and coconut trees bordered the stream.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
